INSERT INTO `catches_fly` VALUES (1,'Alfred\'s Boatman','','Phil Rowley',6,6,'','','water-boatman','flys/water_boatman.png'),(2,'BRIAN\'S SIMPLE SCUD','','Brian Chan',6,10,'','Brian Chan ties up a very innovative Leech Pattern that imitates a variety of lake food sources, like leeches, damselfly nymphs, and even Freshwater Shrimp.','scud','flys/BRIANS_SIMPLE_SCUD.png'),(5,'Anti-Static Bag Chironomid','','Phil Rowley & Brian Chan',7,11,'<p>Brian Chan ties his Anti-Static Bag Wine Chironomid and explains why wine/maroon colors are so important along with talking about how various materials mimic gases trapped by chironomids as they emerge.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This needs to be the standard Chronomid starter fly.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/FDrTEdwkp2M?si=1g8Pnq_oWu-eD_-Q&amp;t=465\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube - FLY FISHING: SPRING CHIRONOMIDS WITH DON FRESCHI</a>&nbsp;</p>','Brian Chan ties his ASB and explains why wine/maroon colors are so important','chironomid','flys/Anti-Static_Bag_Chironomid.png'),(6,'Scud','','Phil Rowley',6,10,'','','scud','flys/plain_old_Scud.png'),(7,'DLT Micro Leech  Damsel Leach Thing','','Brian Chan',6,8,'<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/SF0W3zra7_g\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','Brian Chan ties up a very innovative Leech Pattern that imitates a variety of lake food sources, like leeches, damselfly nymphs, and even Freshwater Shrimp.','leech','flys/DLT_Micro_Leech.png'),(8,'Stimulator','','',5,5,'','','stimulator','flys/Stimulator.png'),(9,'Gold Ribbed Hares Ear','','',1,8,'','','gold-ribbed-hares-ear','flys/Ribbed_hares_ear.png'),(10,'Micro Leech','','',6,4,'','','leech','flys/Mirage_Micro_Leech.png'),(11,'Parachute Adams','','',5,5,'','','caddisfly','flys/Parachute.png'),(12,'ELK HAIR CADDIS','','',5,5,'','','elk-hair-caddis','flys/elk-hair-caddis.jpg'),(14,'Attractor','','',9,NULL,'','','attractor','flys/apps.png'),(15,'Fab','','',9,NULL,'','','fly','flys/FAB_bN3N7oX.png'),(16,'Kazakawich','','',6,NULL,'','','fly','flys/default.jpg'),(17,'Doc Spratley','','',6,NULL,'','','doc-spratley','flys/Doc_Spratly.png'),(18,'Cormorant','','',6,NULL,'','','cormorant','flys/Cormorant.png'),(19,'Chironomid','','',7,11,'','','chironomid','flys/Black_Sally.png'),(21,'Prince Nymph','','',1,9,'','','nymph','flys/Prince_Nymph.png'),(22,'Mosquito','','',5,11,'','','mosiquito','flys/Mosquito.png'),(23,'Pheasant Tail','','',1,NULL,'','','nymph','flys/PHEASANT_TAIL_Nymph.png'),(24,'Grizzly Damsel','','',1,8,'','','fly','flys/Grizzly_Damsel_.png'),(25,'Green Drake','','',5,NULL,'','','fly','flys/Green_Drake.png'),(26,'Dragon Fly','','',1,8,'','','dragonfly','flys/Dragonfly.png'),(28,'Pumpkin Snatcher','','',6,10,'<p>Scuds are a stillwater staple and when present in large concentrations they are a steady staple for&nbsp;stillwater trout. A healthy influx of scuds in the diet allows trout to pack on the pounds. The Pumpkin&nbsp;Snatcher is a suggestive pattern that works well when trout become fixated on scuds.<br />\r\n<strong>Materials</strong><br />\r\nHOOK: Standard dry fly, sizes #10 to #14<br />\r\nBEAD: Glass orange<br />\r\nTHREAD: Olive<br />\r\nRIB: Gold wire<br />\r\nBODY: Green or brown dub<br />\r\nHACKLE: Grizzly, Olive<br />\r\nCHEEKS: Flashabou GoldScuds</p>','TThe Pumpkin Snatcher is a suggestive pattern that works well when trout become fixated on scuds.','scud','flys/Pumpkin_Snatcher.png'),(29,'Ruby Eyed Leech','','Brian Chan',6,4,'<p>Designed by Brian Chan, the Ruby Eyed Leech is a deadly leech pattern. No stillwater fly box would be complete without a few Ruby Eyed Leeches in a variety of colors. This black and red version has performed particularly well. Not surprisingly, this one of our top selling leech patterns on our Stillwater Fly Fishing Store (www.stillwaterflyfishingstore.com)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Materials</strong><br />\r\nHOOK: 10 4X long streamer<br />\r\nTHREAD: Black<br />\r\nBEAD: Brass cone and silver lined red glass<br />\r\nBODY: Black and red Arizona Simi Seal<br />\r\nMake a dubbing bush with re wire.<br />\r\nTAIL: Black and red Arizona Simi Seal</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/8BtIlCeGvN4\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube - PR</a>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<a href=\"https://youtu.be/oZ7qBirJyhE\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube - BC</a></p>','If I only had one leach in the box, this would be it Brian Chan','leech','flys/Ruby_leach.png'),(30,'Peacock Water Boatman','','',6,6,'','','water-boatman','flys/Peacock_Water_Boatman.png'),(31,'Mayfly nymph','','',1,9,'','','mayfly','flys/Mayfly_nymph.png'),(32,'Baby Damsel','','',6,8,'','','damselfly','flys/Baby_Damsel.png'),(33,'Vampire Leech','','',6,4,'<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/nSTVkYhp5SI\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','','leech','flys/Vampire_leech.png'),(34,'Parachute Adams','','',5,9,'<h2>Parachute Adams</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>About The Parachute Adams</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>OK so what gives here, aren&rsquo;t attractors supposed to be bright and flashy?&nbsp; Well most of the time yes, but in this case, it&rsquo;s a general searching mayfly pattern.&nbsp; So we&rsquo;d call this a realistic attractor pattern.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It just works.&nbsp; Most often used in parachute, but also super effective in traditional form, the generally gray body with combined grizzly and brown hackle have made this staple fly since it&rsquo;s invention over 90 years ago.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The jury is actually still out as to whether trout view it as a mayfly, caddis, or just a good meal of something.&nbsp; But it doesn&rsquo;t matter, it catches fish.&nbsp; Carry in sizes 10-18, and be sure to try the smaller sizes as much as the larger.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>How To Tie A Parachute Adams</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Among the best quality fly tyers there is, we like this demonstration by Jim Misiura:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/73FV_cfS1NQ\" target=\"_blank\">Youtube</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','The Adams gray body with combined grizzle and brown hackle have made this a staple dry fly for over 90 years. While no one is certain whether trout view it as a mayfly, caddis, or just a good meal, no matter it just works!','parachute-adams','flys/Parachute_Adams.jpg'),(35,'Fathead Minnow','','',6,NULL,'','','minnow','flys/Fathead_minnow.png'),(36,'San Juan Worm','','',6,11,'<h2>The San Juan Worm</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"san juan worm\" src=\"https://www.flyfishingfieldguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/01/03-21-21-The-San-Juan-Worm-Cover.jpg?x63508\" style=\"height:395px; width:768px\" title=\"03-21-21 The San Juan Worm - Cover\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><em><em>The presence of terrestrial and aquatic worms literally everywhere, super easy to tie, and the killer effectiveness of the San Juan Worm make it one you always want to have as a staple in your box.</em></em></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Our Motto:</strong>&nbsp;Get You To Better Fishing!&nbsp;TM</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &lsquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.flyfishingfieldguides.com/#facebook\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Facebook\">Facebook</a><a href=\"https://www.flyfishingfieldguides.com/#twitter\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Twitter\">Twitter</a><a href=\"https://www.flyfishingfieldguides.com/#pinterest\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Pinterest\">Pinterest</a><a href=\"https://www.flyfishingfieldguides.com/#email\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Email\">Email</a><a href=\"https://www.addtoany.com/share#url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.flyfishingfieldguides.com%2Fsan-juan-worm%2F&amp;title=The%20San%20Juan%20Worm%20Fly%20Pattern%20-%20Fly%20Fishing%20Field%20Guides\">Share</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Note: we are reader supported, through small commissions on affiliate link purchases at no additional cost to you.&nbsp; Thank you for your support!</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h3><img alt=\"san juan worm beadhead\" src=\"https://flyfishingfieldguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/01/San-Juan-Worm-Orange-Bead-Head-V-Rib.jpg?x63508\" style=\"height:395px; width:725px\" /></h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>1. About The San Juan Worm</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>This pattern emulates an aquatic worm which is a staple food for many fish including trout. It is also tied to emulate terrestrial worms.&nbsp; It is used any season, but especially during the spring as its simple construction makes it perfect for fishing during spring rains which wash many worms into the stream where they become easy targets for feeding fish.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As worms are a slow moving food source, swollen with water and soft in texture, trout love to munch on them, thus making The San Juan Juan a perfect choice for fly anglers.&nbsp; As a high-calories-per-bite fish food, San Juan worms can be used to lure larger trout out of their hiding places where they are normally hard to entire.&nbsp; They are also effective for use with bass, panfish, and we&rsquo;ve even seen them take Kokanee after Kokanee when other flies weren&rsquo;t working.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Named after the San Juan river in New Mexico, this pattern is now a staple in many anglers boxes.&nbsp; While it used to create some controversy in the fly fishing world &ndash; is it really an insect imitation or not, as part attractor part natural &ndash; those concerns have subsided as it is fished much like a wooly bugger and is truly a natural food imitation.&nbsp; A newer rubber version has emerged, called the Squirmy Wormy, which has again ignited the &ldquo;is this really a fly&rdquo; debate, but this pattern is also deadly so it is widely used.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s also good to note that the San Juan Worm is that it is very easy to make, thus it is a great pattern for beginner fly tiers.<strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Related Article:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://flyfishingfieldguides.com/best-flies-for-trout/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><em><u>101 Proven Patterns &ndash; Best Flies For Trout</u></em></a></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h3><img alt=\"san juan worm\" src=\"https://flyfishingfieldguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/01/San-Juan-Worm-Brown.jpg?x63508\" style=\"height:424px; width:728px\" /></h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>2. When And How To Fish It</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>As we previously mentioned, perhaps the best time to use the San Juan worm is during the spring as that is the time which is the best suited for fly fishing with this type of pattern. Aquatic worms are &nbsp;prevalent all over the world, so the San Juan worm can be used both in large water surfaces and in small creeks and brooks, year round actually.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here are a few tips on how to fly fish with this pattern:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up your fly rod and dead drift it like using a trailing nymph along the bottom column.</li>\r\n	<li>Use an indicator or add a split shot so you can get the perfect depth, it is important to have a perfect weight split especially if you are fishing in the fast flowing waters.</li>\r\n	<li>This pattern works great with low light fishing.</li>\r\n	<li>Using it as a worm and trying to imitate the real life conditions will yield the best result while using the San Juan Worm.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><img alt=\"san juan worm pink\" src=\"https://flyfishingfieldguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/01/San-Juan-Worm-Pink.jpg?x63508\" style=\"height:613px; width:1200px\" /></h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>3. Tie It, or Buy It?</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The San Juan worm is as easy as it gets to ties as it will take you only ten minutes to get it done. It doesn&rsquo;t require any special skills or materials which makes it a great choice for a person who had just started with this type of angling. Many fly anglers had also learned this pattern first as it is the simplest one. This is why we recommend that it is great to tie as step towards learning how to make other more difficult patterns.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><img alt=\"san juan worm\" src=\"https://flyfishingfieldguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/01/San-Juan-Worm-Yellow-e1616474307727.jpg?x63508\" style=\"height:344px; width:602px\" /></h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>4. Basic Recipe Card</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Along with Griffith&rsquo;s Gnat, this may be the shortest recipe card you&rsquo;ll ever see!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Hook:</strong>&nbsp;standard nymph or wet fly hook in sizes 12 to 14, but really nearly any hook will work fine</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Thread:</strong>&nbsp;color to match body, in weight 6/0.&nbsp; May also contrast body</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Body:</strong>&nbsp;red ultra-Chenille, or other color you may choose (brown, tan, pink are the most common besides red, but other such as yellow, purple and fluorescent colors work too), ok to get creative here</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Related Article:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://flyfishingfieldguides.com/beginner-fly-tying-easy-fly-patterns/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><em><u>Beginner Fly Tying &ndash; 14 Easy Patterns</u></em></a></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h3><img alt=\"squirmy worm\" src=\"https://flyfishingfieldguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/01/Squirmy-Worm-Red.jpg?x63508\" style=\"height:470px; width:700px\" /></h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>5. Variations</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The pink San Juan Worm is great for catching trout and many other species, with glistening highlights make it look more natural, you can use chenille and make it look like two clusters which will be more attractive to the fish. Common variations include:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Different colors including red, brown, purple, yellow, green or color of your choice</li>\r\n	<li>Some people tie these to be as realistic as possible, others as total attractor patterns</li>\r\n	<li>Using a brass or plastic bead head to emulate the thicker mid-section of the worm</li>\r\n	<li>Tying the shape more like an inchworm with a tall hump</li>\r\n	<li>Singing the ends with a lighter to make them look more pointy and darker tips like a real worm</li>\r\n	<li>Dual-colored, e.g. red on one end, brown on the other</li>\r\n	<li>Contrasting color chenille vs. bead to stand out in murky water</li>\r\n	<li>Using rubber instead of chenille to create the Squirmy Wormy</li>\r\n	<li>Articulated 2nd hook longer version (think nightcrawler sized)</li>\r\n	<li>Tungsten jig version that basically has a long worm as a tail, body ending in a bead head</li>\r\n	<li>Fuzzy or psycho mid-section (even with hackle)</li>\r\n</ul>','The presence of terrestrial and aquatic worms literally everywhere, super easy to tie, and the killer effectiveness of the San Juan Worm make it one you always want to have as a staple in your box.','san-juan-worm','flys/San_Juan_Worm.jpeg'),(37,'Fathead Minnow','','Phil Rowley',8,15,'','','minnow','flys/Fathead_Minnow.png'),(38,'Brian Chan Maribou Micro Leech','','Brian Chan',6,4,'','This pattern was demonstrated at NLFT-Trout Unlimited Seminar in Edmonton.  January 2013','leech','flys/Maribou_Micro_Leech.png'),(39,'Balanced Leech-Bruised','','Phil Rowley',6,4,'<p>The Bruised Leech is one of my favorite color combinations, whether a traditional cast and retrieve fly or this balanced version. In 2013 this was probably my most successful balanced leech producing throughout the season. Thanks to John Rohmer for coming up with #21 Black &amp; Blue Simi Seal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://Balanced Leech-Bruised\" target=\"_blank\">Youtube</a></p>','The Bruised Leech is one of my favorite color combinations','leech','flys/Bruised_Leech.png'),(40,'Slush Jelly or Slush Blob','','',9,16,'<p>Hook: Daiichi 1120 (#10-#12) (<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/redirect?event=video_description&amp;redi