ion&amp;redir_token=QUFFLUhqbXVlZjFtU3ZZTXp0ckJxOURPd0F2QnBVRUs4d3xBQ3Jtc0tsT0lMUy1DR1FrR0ZQVDdtTm9oWHhVbG1IS0FqOFdOeEVrMkxTT3BLRmNkU2Nrd2JwUkRoeTR1Z1B4LXBXdjFRQ2oxdDhaZDJ4ckJlNFgzMTNuZFZZMjRYNnlDYXlVZ3VHNExNVmNqamJaZFAtSVhqQQ&amp;q=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.canadianllama.com%2Fbrass-beads%2F%3Freferrer%3DCNWR_33041533934888&amp;v=Y7Ew2WSfcjk\" rel=\"nofollow\" tabindex=\"0\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.canadianllama.com/brass-b...</a>) or Tungsten (<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/redirect?event=video_description&amp;redir_token=QUFFLUhqblpfNGxrQVJFdzI4a3RNQXdlY1JScHExZFlMQXxBQ3Jtc0ttVm5XWVhNN3JpN2Q3MFVFdGJBNndreVo2VXdMYVdXcDJuSEFyZFBSTUVHRUFrby02RWlIODZyanlQODVUNFFmZ2g1SFBuM3R6MGRYLS1RdEJYNURxOVY5NGJKWjZPaUkxak9QRnowWDA1Y3p3NmQzSQ&amp;q=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.canadianllama.com%2Ftungsten-beads%2F%3Freferrer%3DCNWR_33041533934888&amp;v=Y7Ew2WSfcjk\" rel=\"nofollow\" tabindex=\"0\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.canadianllama.com/tungste...</a>) You can suspend this pattern beneath a strike indicator when trout are suspended in deep water. Or fish it aggressively using a brisk 4-6-inch strip pause retrieve using a sinking line. This pattern can also be used to attract or draw fish into other, perhaps more natural, patterns when using multiple flies. If you want to learn more about how to fly fish lakes please download and subscribe to mine and Brian Chan&rsquo;s Stillwater Fly Fishing App by selecting the appropriate link below. Our app includes specific tips on how we fish attractors including indicator tactics. One of the app benefits is the ability to take our helpful content with you wherever you go. Once downloaded to your smartphone, Wi-Fi is not needed to access the over 100 video tips, and growing, contained across five different chapters, Entomology, Leaders &amp; Knots, Strategies and Tactics, Equipment, and Stillwater Flies.</p>','A favorite attractor fly of mine when trout are feeding on zooplankton.','zooplankton','flys/Slush_Jelly.png'),(41,'Modified Zucchini Chironomid Pupa Fly','','Phil Rowley',7,11,'','Hard to improve on our time tested & proven Zucchini chironomid pupa fly pattern, but we did think it would be an interesting take to put a bit of a classic buzzer spin to it! Whip some up and see what you think ... :)','chironomid','flys/Zucchini.png'),(42,'Black Olive','','Phil Rowley',7,11,'<p>If you take a close look at a lot of the &ldquo;black&rdquo; chironomids in your samples you&rsquo;ll quickly notice they will often actually be a very dark olive colour. This pattern will work when fish are on those or just the usual olive colours you see. Twist it up and have em for the spring and up your cronie game!</p>','','chironomids','flys/Black_Olive.png'),(43,'Pale Olive Chironomid','','Brian Chan',7,11,'<p>https://youtu.be/frOvGIYJzIs</p>','Brian Chan and Don Freschi show to viewer how to effectively fly fish for Rainbow trout using Shallow Water Chironomid Techniques. Don ties his Pale Olive Chironomid on the bench.','chironomid','flys/Pale_Olive_Chironomid.png'),(44,'Reaper Midge','','',5,11,'','Reaper Midge Fly Tying Tutorial | The Fly Fiend.','midge','flys/Reaper_Midge.png'),(45,'Elk Hair Emerger Nymph','','',1,5,'<p>https://www.youtube.com/shorts/kVvMmh3XkH4</p>','Uses Dubbing over elk hair to make it super buoyant.','caddisfly','flys/Elk_Hair_Emerger_Nymph.png'),(46,'Pheasant Tail','','',1,5,'<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/hr5ZIqaynAw\" target=\"_blank\">https://youtu.be/hr5ZIqaynAw</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Copies many different nymphs.&nbsp; Tie it in many colours, sizes and weights.</p>','','pheasant-tail','flys/Pheasent_tail.png'),(47,'Egg','','',6,NULL,'<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/hr5ZIqaynAw?t=173\" target=\"_blank\">Youtube</a></p>','','egg','flys/Egg_fly.png'),(48,'Conehead Wooly Bugger','','',1,NULL,'<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/hr5ZIqaynAw?t=315\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','','Wooly','flys/conehead_wolly_bugger.png'),(49,'Egg Laying Caddis','','',6,5,'','','caddis','flys/Egg_Laying_Caddis.png'),(50,'The Alaskan Carey','','Phil Rowley',1,8,'<p>Hook: Daiichi 1710 #6-#10</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thread: MFC 8/0 or UTC 70 Olive</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tail: Guinea, Dyed Green</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Body: Variegated Chenille, Brown/Black</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hackle: Guinea, Dyed Green</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Carey Special is one of my favorite suggestive patterns. Depending on the size and color it can be used to suggest a variety of different prey items. I use it most often as a suggestive representation of a dragonfly nymph or caddis pupa. It&#39;s buggy look make a good general searching pattern too.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To learn more about dragonfly nymphs, caddis pupa and the flies and presentation methods I prefer to use please download and subscribe to mine and Brian Chan&rsquo;s Stillwater Fly Fishing App by selecting the appropriate link below.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One of the app benefits is the ability to take our helpful content with you wherever you go. Once downloaded to your smartphone, Wi-Fi is not needed to access the over 100 video tips, and growing, contained across five different chapters, Entomology, Leaders &amp; Knots, Strategies and Tactics, Equipment and Stillwater Flies.</p>','I use it most often as a suggestive representation of a dragonfly nymph or caddis pupa. It\'s buggy look make a good general searching pattern too.','dragonfly','flys/Dragonfly_nymph.png'),(51,'Bionic Worm','','Phil Rowley',7,11,'<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/gh-jVFL0TBI\" target=\"_blank\">Youtube</a></p>','Here is a deadly chironomid larva pattern originally designed by Jerry McBride.  This pattern drives fish crazy all over western Canada and the United States.','chironomid','flys/Bionic_worm.png'),(52,'Phil\'s Black and Red PBR','','Phil Rowley',7,11,'<p>The PBR is one of my favorite chironomid pupa patterns. Its overall black and red coloration matches the predominant color of most chironomid pupa. This pattern has produced all over North America. If I am not sure which color to start with its always black and red and almost always a PBR</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/4AVjceCAd58\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','Its overall black and red coloration matches the predominant color of most chironomid pupa.','chironomid','flys/Black__Red_PRB.png'),(53,'Stillwater Callibaetis','','Phil Rowley',1,9,'<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/-S8W5VP4IuY\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','Callibaetis nymphs are one of my favorite food sources to imitate.  In the productive clear water lakes of western North America slender natural looking patterns perform best.  The Stillwater Callibaetis, along with my Herl May, is one of my favorites.','callibaetis','flys/Callibaetis.png'),(54,'Pine Squirrel Zonker','','Phil Rowley',8,15,'<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/6wlQd9XSHWQ\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','The Squirrel Zonker is a simple baitfish pattern that has worked well for me, particularly on the minnow rich waters of SW Manitoba.  Micro squirrel and mink Zonker strips are perfect for small minnow patterns.','minnow','flys/Pine_Squirrel_Zonker.png'),(55,'Zebra Midge','','',7,11,'<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/_iwqOpFZoYk\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','Likely derived from Dick Thompson\'s TDC (Thompson\'s Delectable Chironomid), the Zebra Midge is one of the easiest, most effective flies out there. Can be fished year-round in rivers and stillwaters to equal effect.','chironomid','flys/Zebra_Midge.png'),(56,'Reaper Midge','','',5,11,'<p>Are you a tailwater junkie? Do you enjoy fishing for big midge fed trout during cold winter months while the fair weather fishers are warm at home tying flies? If so, you need some Reaper Midges in your fly box. This pattern created by Josh Williams of Dead Drift Outfitters has become a staple in my midge dry box. It is simple to tie and offers some versatility in how it is fished. The flash abdomen and wing are not only eye-catching to fishers but also the fish. The build on this fly with a traditional palmered hackle allows you to either cure it heavily with floatant to keep it riding high or if need be you can go light on the floatant and allow it to dip just under the surface film as an emerging midge. Either way, this pattern fishes great when midges are on the move.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/EmCCNDyryr4\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','How to tie The Reaper Midge | AvidMax Fly Tying Tuesday Tutorials','midge','flys/Reaper_Midge_aoVAxi2.png'),(57,'Baby Damsel','','Brian Chan',1,8,'<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/Ikk8imk_ngM?t=1024\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','','damselfly','flys/Baby_Damsel_Vm2pHXM.png'),(58,'Callibaetis Cruncher','','Phil Rowley',1,9,'<p>When trout are off the bottom feeding on ascending Callibaetis nymphs, this Cruncher variation is my go-to fly. The pattern descends slowly, keeping it in the feeding zone. To fish, this fly, use a floating or Midge Tip line, a slow five-turn hand twist, mixed with prolonged pauses. This version of a Cruncher is also an excellent searching pattern on any lake home to a healthy Callibaetis pattern.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/AkxYopkshNE\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','When trout are off the bottom feeding on ascending Callibaetis nymphs, this Cruncher variation is my go-to fly.','Callibaetis','flys/Cruncher.png'),(59,'Black N Silver Red Butt (Fall Flash Variant)','','',7,11,'<p>A staple chironomid pupa fly pattern with a bit of flash variation that seems to give it an edge in the fall! Giver a go and see what you think!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/xIVAoXc1Aw0\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','A staple chironomid pupa fly pattern with a bit of flash variation that seems to give it an edge in the fall!','chironomid','flys/Black__Silver_Red_Butt.png'),(60,'Zebra Midge','','',7,11,'<p><strong>Tying the midge lifecycle</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Materials:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>- Crystal Flash (any color)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Ultra wire (Silver)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Grizzly Hackle (To match hook)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-60 Degree hook (18-22)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Emerger hook (18-22)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/ubCxcAkkcgA?t=120\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','Larvel Stage: Zebra Midge','midge','flys/Zebra_Midge_7jpm4as.png'),(61,'Hackel Stacker Midge','','',7,11,'<p>Materials:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Crystal Flash (any color)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Ultra wire (Silver)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Grizzly Hackle (To match hook)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-60 Degree hook (18-22)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Emerger hook (18-22)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/ubCxcAkkcgA?t=296\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','Emerger stage: Hackel Stacker Midge','chironomid','flys/Hackel_Stacker_Midge.png'),(62,'Crystal Midge','','',5,11,'<p>Materials:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Crystal Flash (any color)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Ultra wire (Silver)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Grizzly Hackle (To match hook)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-60 Degree hook (18-22)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Emerger hook (18-22)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>see:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://youtu.be/ubCxcAkkcgA?t=514\" target=\"_blank\">Youtube</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>These are my three favorite Midge patterns to represent the three major stages in this little bugs lifecycle. Tying the midge pupa, midge emerger, and midge fly are all fairly simple and extremely effective. These are my go to patterns for winter time fishing or if I were to stumble upon a cheeky tailwater.</p>','Fly Stage: Crystal Midge','chironomid','flys/Crystal_Midge.png'),(63,'CHAN\'S WINDOW TINT CHIRONOMID','','Brian Chan',7,11,'<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/vJvy0qfU44A\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','Brian Chan talks about the KEY elements of tying an effective Chironomid pattern, while he ties one of his personal favorites.','chironomid','flys/Window_tint.png'),(64,'Tequila Booby','','Phil Rowley',6,16,'<p>The Booby is perhaps the ultimate stillwater attractor. Nothing in lake looks or moves like a Booby. Fish this pattern on a full sinking type V or greater sinking line using a brisk 4-6 inch strip retrieve. This pattern can also be used on the surface as a disturbance pattern or the point fly on a washing line set up. Be prepared takes are usually savage.</p>','','booby','flys/Tequila_Booby.png'),(65,'Size 30 Midge','','',7,11,'<p><a href=\"https://youtube.com/shorts/yDviL9Emh-k?feature=share\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','Can Cheech Tie a Size 30 Midge With His Gigantic Hands?','chironomid','flys/tiny_midge.png'),(66,'Elk Hair Caddis','','',5,5,'<p><a href=\"https://youtube.com/shorts/818jIexDOOI?feature=share\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','','caddis','flys/EHC.png'),(67,'G.I.M.P. (Good In Most Places) Nymph','','',1,NULL,'<h1><a href=\"https://youtu.be/xS9_GwVaZAM\" target=\"_blank\">FLY TYING: THE G.I.M.P. (Good In Most Places) Nymph</a></h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Deb Paskall ties a great lil nymph pattern that works well in Saltwater along with Interior Lakes and rivers. It&#39;s a simple pattern to tie for beginners and very effective, as it imitates a variety of aquatic insects. Hook: Size 10 Curved Nymph Thread: 8/0 Semperfli Waxed black Tail/Hackle: Pheasant Tail Body: Peacock Sparkle Chenille</p>','It\'s a simple pattern to tie for beginners and very effective, as it imitates a variety of aquatic insects.','nymph','flys/GIMP_Nymph.png'),(68,'The Foam Arse Blob','','',9,16,'<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/aozfw4XOC1A\" target=\"_blank\">Fly Tying Tutorial: The Foam Arse Blob - STILLWATER fly pattern - FAB</a></p>','This is about as easy as it gets!  We tie up the popular stillwater fly fishing pattern, the Foam Arse Blob (FAB)','blob','flys/FAB_beyPIjY.png'),(69,'BRENT\'S PERCH JIG FLY','','',8,15,'<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/0Hb-Indu_5Y\" target=\"_blank\">BRENT&#39;S PERCH JIG FLY</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>List of Ingredients</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hook: Gamakatsu Jig#1 Thread: 3/0 Olive</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bead: Large Gold Conehead Weight: 0.035 Lead Free Wire Body: Orange/Olive Slinky Fibre, Off White/Camo SF Fibres, Mirro Orange Semperflash Mirage Eyes: 5/16&quot; Gold Ultra Eyes Finish: UV Resin &amp; Markers.</p>','Brent Schlenker, the Fly Tyin\' Cowboy, ties another outstanding Baitfish Pattern that attracts many Fresh and Saltwater gamefish.','minnow','flys/perch.png'),(70,'\"None Of Your Business\"','','',6,NULL,'<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/CqChsq4PHXE\" target=\"_blank\">Youtube</a></p>','Tim Flagler is fishing the Gander River and ties the deadly wet fly known by Newfoundlaners as \"None-of-your-business\". Wicked fly for salmon and sea-run trout.','wetfly','flys/NoYB.png'),(71,'Denny\'s Stillwater Nymph','','Denny Rickards',1,NULL,'<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/H5Gc3-WXzFI\" target=\"_blank\">FLY TYING: Denny&#39;s Stillwater Nymph</a></p>','Brent Schlenker ties one of Denny Rickards popular lake nymph patterns. This fly imitates a variety of lake insects and always produces.','nymph','flys/Dennys_stillwater_nymph.png'),(72,'Chan\'s Magic Brown Leech','','Brian Chan',6,4,'<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/lK6U1lGD5OM\" target=\"_blank\">FLY TYING: Chan&#39;s Magic Brown Leech</a></p>','Don ties up Brian Chan\'s most productive Leech pattern on Sheridan Lake.','leech','flys/Magic_Brown_Leech.png'),(73,'Glenn\'s leech','','Phil Rowley',6,4,'<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/PVTU2vJvAx4\" target=\"_blank\">Youtube</a></p>','I first featured this pattern in my first book Fly Patterns for Stillwaters.  To this day it remains one of my favorite leech patterns, particularly during the fall months.','leech','flys/Glenns_leech.png'),(74,'FLY TYING: BRENT\'S SF SMALL BAITFISH','','',8,15,'<p>Brent Schlenker, the Fly Tyin&#39; Cowboy, ties another outstanding Baitfish Pattern that attracts many Fresh and Saltwater gamefish. List of Ingredients Hook: Size 4 TMC 800S Thread: 6/0 Black Body/Wing: SF Predator Fibres, Polar Bear, Red Poly Bear, SF Cashmere Monkey, Pale Olive &amp; Black, SF Crystal Pearl, SF Gaula/Green Blend Eyes: 1/4&quot; Blue Ultra Eyes</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/FLOJe8ih5dQ\" target=\"_blank\">Youtube</a></p>','','minnow','flys/small_baitfish.png'),(75,'Boogie Man','','Phil Rowley',6,4,'<p>Hanging leeches under indicators is now common on most western Canadian stillwaters. Arguably, you could spend the entire season suspending only chironomids and leeches under indicators and consistently take fish. In recent years, tiny micro leeches have evolved adding yet another dimension to this deadly presentation option. Bob Taylor&#39;s Boogie Man micro leech is an excellent example.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/FSqCzzbArzU\" target=\"_blank\">Youtube</a></p>','Hanging leeches under indicators is now common on most western Canadian stillwaters','leech','flys/Boogie_man.png'),(76,'The Blue Winged Olive (BWO) Dun - Fly Tying with Geoff Johnston','','',5,5,'<p>The Blue winged Olive Dun is one of the dries that I employ during a hatch of BWO&#39;s on our waters. The underbody is trimmed to allow the fly to sit on the water, so that the fan-shaped mix of hackle and EP fibre wing, hopefully, creates a similar footprint to the natural. This fly can be tied in a variety of sizes and colours to mimic different species of upwings. Dressing: Hook: Kamasan B405 or B170 Size 16 Thread: Olive 8/0 Uni-Thread Abdomen/Thorax: Olive Super Fine dubbing Wing - BWO EP Trigger Point International Fibres Hackle: Blue Dun Cock Hackle</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/p2kmtXpGl1I\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','','caddisfly','flys/BWO_Dun.png'),(77,'Midge Emerger - Fly tying with Geoff Johnston','','',5,11,'<p>This &#39;Midge Emerger&#39; has proved quite effective for me when used to imitate emerging midge and/or crippled midge that are trapped in the meniscus and being picked off by the trout. Dressing: Hook: Size 18 - 22 Tiemco 2487 or 2488 Thread: Black 8/0 Uni-Thread Thorax: Black (Hare or Zelon) Dubbing Wing: Black or Dark Grey CDC Feathers Secondary Wing: Pearl Krystal Flash My name is Geoff Johnston. I am a full-time fly-fishing guide and tutor on the River Eden and it&#39;s tributaries. I also guide and teach on lakes in the Lakes District like Ullswater and Haweswater. For more information check out my website at <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/redirect?event=video_description&amp;redir_token=QUFFLUhqbm9Mb2JTQkx5S1lYeXRfRllqOGl5UTIzazRXUXxBQ3Jtc0trMjJHV1h0bkY1TjFNMjM0cE9hQmxpc2p5OXk1WkZEUU9aTVZBNjh1bHc1RGphVTYtZG1jUGRxRjlCS3gyeDFWdUhKNEtabzlWWXYxbHNpbjZOOGtNemxQRDg4eUlZZVh5QUFJc2xLaVpGMm5yYVpQYw&amp;q=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.theedenangler.co.uk%2F&amp;v=CsEcJ9MpEsE\" rel=\"nofollow\" tabindex=\"0\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.theedenangler.co.uk/</a>. I hope that you enjoy my videos and thanks for watching.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/CsEcJ9MpEsE\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','This \'Midge Emerger\' has proved quite effective for me when used to imitate emerging midge and/or crippled midge that are trapped in the meniscus and being picked off by the trout.','chironomid','flys/Midge_Emerger.png'),(78,'Extended Body Ephemera Danica','','',5,11,'<p>Forgive the slightly croaky voice - I&rsquo;m just getting over a (non-covid) sore throat. This is a cracking pattern to represent E. danica and the other big mayflies. Tying these long-bodied flies on a long shank hook is one option, but this gives a very straight (and very heavy) fly that doesn&rsquo;t look quite right in my eyes. This technique for extended bodies is very similar to how I tied the damselfly in my previous upload, but using moose and elk to create a banded mayfly body with loads of floatation power. Top it off with some Wally wings and a big bushy hackle, and this is an easy to tie but very effective mayfly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/EY3fJw3xQmA\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','This is a cracking pattern to represent E. danica and the other big mayflies.','chironomid','flys/Mayfly_adult.png'),(79,'\'LDO Emerger\'','','',5,11,'<p>The &#39;LDO Emerger&#39; is tied to imitate the emerging stage of our Large Dark Olive (Baetis Rhodani). Dressing: Hook: Size 12 Kamasan B100 Abdomen: Brown Olive Super Fine Dubbing Rib: No. 10 Glo-Brite Fluorescent Floss Wing: 2 - 4 Natural CDC feathers Thorax: Hare&#39;s mask/Pearl Ice Dub mix</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/VpdYXAT4bYc\" target=\"_blank\">Youtube</a></p>','Large Dark Olive','chironomid','flys/LDO_Emerger.png'),(80,'The LDO (Large Dark Olive) nymph','','',1,11,'<p>The LDO Nymph is tied to represent the mature nymph of the Large Dark Olive which hatches on my local rivers in the Spring and Autumn. Dressing; Hook: Size 12 Kamasan B175 Thread: Olive Dun 8/0 UNI-Thread Abdomen/Thorax: Dark Olive Awesome Possum Dubbing Rib: Glo-brite Floss No. 10 My name is Geoff Johnston. I am a full-time fly-fishing guide and tutor on the River Eden and it&#39;s tributaries. I also guide and teach on lakes in the Lakes District like Ullswater and Haweswater. For more information check out my website at <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/redirect?event=video_description&amp;redir_token=QUFFLUhqbHJ2LTdfUTRjYzBLbXhHaEg2Y2FuVWdqMi1jd3xBQ3Jtc0trM3FGX1BMbE1PVjJLWVRmLWRQb2JsNnBUcmNBaHZsUVROMHVkVEFnWGxHZkdJeXZSZXVscjdXaDl3T1hFZEtGUGhJTkFhdE1hVHJRRWRxc3VTeUJPbWdydjItWFBxUzdkVzhaY25jUlktV21OQ2ljcw&amp;q=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.theedenangler.co.uk%2F&amp;v=mNGAM7XX0J4\" rel=\"nofollow\" tabindex=\"0\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.theedenangler.co.uk/</a>. I hope that you enjoy my videos, please subscribe if you do and thanks for watching.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/mNGAM7XX0J4\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','The LDO Nymph is tied to represent the mature nymph of the Large Dark Olive which hatches on my local rivers in the Spring and Autumn.','chironomid','flys/LDO_Nymph.png'),(81,'Super Stretch Midge Larva','','',7,11,'<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you want to tie an easy but effective bloodworm or midge/chironomid larva pattern, it doesn&#39;t get much easier than this. We use Hareline&#39;s new Midge Stretch Rib for this awesome effect.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/syoNXG3TesY\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','','chironomid','flys/Midge_Larva.png'),(82,'Olive Emerger','','',5,NULL,'<p>Emerger imitations are an important addition to any fly fisherman&#39;s box and I wouldn&#39;t be without my &#39;Olive Emerger&#39;. I carry it in sizes 12 to 16 to cover a variety of olives that hatch on the rivers in my area. Dressing: Hook: Size 12 - 16 Kamasan B100 Abdomen: Olive Super Fine Dubbing Wing: 2 - 4 Natural CDC feathers Thorax: Hare&#39;s mask/Pearl Ice Dub mix</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/1NYsedgwHcE\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','','emerger','flys/Olive_Emerger.png'),(83,'Mylar floating minnow','','',8,15,'<h1>Tuan Nguyen Mylar floating minnow</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/xzxOq46s2bQ\" target=\"_blank\">Youtube</a></p>','Tuan demonstrates some great techniques in this floating minnow pattern.','minnow','flys/Mylar_floating_minnow.png'),(84,'The March Brown Nymph','','',1,NULL,'<p>This is my March Brown Nymph. This flat bodied stone-clinger nymph imitation has proved successful enough to earn it&#39;s place in my fly box over the last few years and it is normally my go-to nymph when the March Brown hatches in Eden during late March and early April. Dressing: Hook: Size 10 Kamasan B110 Thorax cover: 4 - 5mm strip of Brown Flexibody Weight: 1 - 2mm strip of Veniard Adhesive Lead Foil Tail: 6 - 8 Cock Pheasant Tail Fibres Abdomen: Dark Brown Hare-Tron dubbing Rib: Wide/broad Copper wire Thorax: Hare&#39;s mask/Pearl Ice Dub mix</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/G04X15Mp6kI\" target=\"_blank\">Youtube</a></p>','','nymph','flys/March_brown_nymph.png'),(85,'Micro Scud','','',6,10,'<p>Everyone needs a good go-to scud pattern in their box! Scuds can be a great food source for trout, and oftentimes they target naturals that are really really small. Because we want the proportions to be spot on, we have eliminated extra materials like scud back and wire that might make the fly too heavy. I&rsquo;ve fished this style a lot in stillwaters and the fish whole heartedly agree that it looks good enough to eat. Feel free to make these in sowbug colors, or even with an orange egg sac Material List: <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/redirect?event=video_description&amp;redir_token=QUFFLUhqbS1QZ0J4TnRyck0zblpfWVZ1aWw1X0F0ejVOQXxBQ3Jtc0trdVU5dU1fc1hHbi13VV8tTVltejUtQ0ZTQzJ4YWJteC1HRkZTdkhJeXAxMjZKNUZWWVFTSG5IOHU5d2RoYXdDdDUwTTlIMmJJeTh6OXNBQ2MyN1NqbERRdGlDbzctMVNwekNiMElhangxZmtaSkZrTQ&amp;q=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.flyfishfood.com%2Fblogs%2Fstillwater-tutorials%2Fmicro-scud&amp;v=JXHlWe16edI\" rel=\"nofollow\" tabindex=\"0\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.flyfishfood.com/blogs/sti...</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/JXHlWe16edI\" target=\"_blank\">Youtube</a></p>','Scuds can be a great food source for trout, and oftentimes they target naturals that are really really small.','scud','flys/Micro_scud.png'),(86,'Micro Caddis Pupa','','',6,5,'<p>In this fly tying tutorial, Cheech ties the Micro Caddis Pupa Caddis make up a HUGE part of what fish eat in lots of western trout streams, but the majority of them in the fly bins are TOO BIG! Size down your pupa and see what happens... This is a really cool fly that uses only one material, but make sure to follow the instruction on the dubbing loop to ensure you get the taper that is needed. this is a bug you can&#39;t ignore! Material List: <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/redirect?event=video_description&amp;redir_token=QUFFLUhqbnFHVWtOMlo0bkFjUjdZbkJUc2hIUGdIdC02QXxBQ3Jtc0ttZWVGcktpYl93Z05sNWhLR3FSMUFYYlR3amVVUUl3OTd6SFlDVWRtZFlnQjV6ZU1wdmRPMjRmSnhnOExtY0dsNWt5LUJhYVdqVWluMTJPQTZ5emNCSGRzUTdRNGs0elg5RE1WVFhyRlhaeEhwT1lCdw&amp;q=https%3A%2F%2F