pt3lwo\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','','chironomid','flys/Chans_Chironomid.png'),(90,'Oive Woolly Bugger','','',6,4,'<p>Detailed instructions for tying an Olive Woolly Bugger Fly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hook: 4X-long streamer hook (here a Dai-Riki 700), size 2-12.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bead:&nbsp;Gold, 5/32-inch.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thread:&nbsp;6/0 or 140 Denier, brown olive. Weight:&nbsp;Lead-free wire, .02.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tail: Olive marabou blood quill, tips removed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Body:&nbsp;Olive chenille.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hackle:&nbsp;Olive grizzly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/7Ku1-lnkKzI\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','','leech','flys/Olive_Wolly_Bugger.png'),(91,'Hare\'s Ear','','',1,5,'<p>The Hare&#39;s Ear is one of the most popular, time-tested fly patterns out there. It&#39;s simple, yet very effective at putting fish in the net. This fly fishing fly is also a great pattern for beginners to start learning how to tie nymphs. In this fly tying tutorial, we&#39;ll show you the step by step instructions so you can start fly tying with confidence.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>MATERIALS:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Standard Nymph Hook - <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/redirect?event=video_description&amp;redir_token=QUFFLUhqbTRWaVo1T1FkaGNqUjlrRlhJTEUwN1dVSXJZd3xBQ3Jtc0tsUVJYbHFWQm9zYWtrc0V6M19tTzB5WUd2Q0kySDNNb3JSeG5ScTR1ZU9jZVBhVi1RTWVCZk1lNThfelNYZXppNURyZlJDSzFZUUs3R1VnUFhid3loZ0ZKZU1GT1o0MFBvVjNkMGZuMFBfX0dIaUFLaw&amp;q=https%3A%2F%2Frebrand.ly%2Fhares-ear-hook&amp;v=zgWQ9QsvHdo\" rel=\"nofollow\" tabindex=\"0\" target=\"_blank\">https://rebrand.ly/hares-ear-hook</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Brass Bead - <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/redirect?event=video_description&amp;redir_token=QUFFLUhqbDl6V0NoWTVJd0xIcm95am1PcFJMNnB6bjhmQXxBQ3Jtc0tucXhsRlIxVEhHdVdMYjNKMTNMTW9sellFWXBmOGh4RXFUMnlxeDhXb01aaE9vM3IwY2s4eURnQnluOWN0cUhkYjd0c2hnZW1rYnFBWFRpby1ZY1hvM3FERXlKQUtOdENEMUNYR3EtRE9UTWZfS2NmZw&amp;q=https%3A%2F%2Frebrand.ly%2Fhares-ear-bead&amp;v=zgWQ9QsvHdo\" rel=\"nofollow\" tabindex=\"0\" target=\"_blank\">https://rebrand.ly/hares-ear-bead</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thread - <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/redirect?event=video_description&amp;redir_token=QUFFLUhqbU9sazhZSElzLXhwSmN2b0YyTWFRZ21VS1dBQXxBQ3Jtc0ttV2N2MlVNWTFDeUN2RGdvTmFEQkxfY2RDXzI2Ml9lRTVrb2tSLWJtNFdrZzF3V3FBM1ZqU1ZOV2hZSU5hNFJURE5DUngwNS1UZDVHeWIyVVNhalNTbzlPc0ViV3pwaXI1MFA0YkFkc1VIdC1UdEJkTQ&amp;q=https%3A%2F%2Frebrand.ly%2Fhares-ear-thread&amp;v=zgWQ9QsvHdo\" rel=\"nofollow\" tabindex=\"0\" target=\"_blank\">https://rebrand.ly/hares-ear-thread</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pheasant tail - <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/redirect?event=video_description&amp;redir_token=QUFFLUhqbkJDMGZNZDJqWno3Mk12OWIyYjR5NXVyRURqZ3xBQ3Jtc0tsNVhzc3pHckNRNk50Tk1teGVEazJEbDlvRzA4ckdYeGlyYjg2djlObk1iMkxxX3cxOGppd2V6c1kxeDh3aEFfajNqRE5jcnZva3Rxd2QzaDVVbVNxUllLdDB1blFQdnkzakdlY3JnVXZ5WjZiaEhObw&amp;q=https%3A%2F%2Frebrand.ly%2Fhares-ear-pheasant-tail&amp;v=zgWQ9QsvHdo\" rel=\"nofollow\" tabindex=\"0\" target=\"_blank\">https://rebrand.ly/hares-ear-pheasant...</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wire - <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/redirect?event=video_description&amp;redir_token=QUFFLUhqa3E4eWJsZkkxVVluWnZIMGo1NkVtOXZ5dlEwQXxBQ3Jtc0tuRVpoRzhWVEdtOGNIeU9SR0xXZExHb3l3cFUzVlRjU0NpaWNibm1tMFNOa3lKeFFZVk9zLUNLM1R1d0tSUVZsQzN2U2VHQ0VyYi1BSlR4ampBOFZZeTJsbzFVR21RNjVRUlZKaHV4dVhHUTRWa05pbw&amp;q=https%3A%2F%2Frebrand.ly%2Fhares-ear-wire&amp;v=zgWQ9QsvHdo\" rel=\"nofollow\" tabindex=\"0\" target=\"_blank\">https://rebrand.ly/hares-ear-wire</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hare&#39;s Ear Dubbing - <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/redirect?event=video_description&amp;redir_token=QUFFLUhqbTB5cnk4WktjaVZINjJkYXN2SkkxOWk0eHlrQXxBQ3Jtc0ttUjVoSVIwY203c08yRWtMaV9kdnF1ZG45MHJOYUhoejFMNEROSDdKQXZpM190dmthNjE4aE5iS3Fyd0o0TDhTNWRyZTdlRU80czhEQzZMTlJ1OUhMNjV2U2xMRVZwallqSFJWWXYyMm9lUlN2SlpTWQ&amp;q=https%3A%2F%2Frebrand.ly%2Fhares-ear-dubbing&amp;v=zgWQ9QsvHdo\" rel=\"nofollow\" tabindex=\"0\" target=\"_blank\">https://rebrand.ly/hares-ear-dubbing</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/zgWQ9QsvHdo?si=L9wTUcouUHJmETkr\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube video</a></p>','','caddisfly','flys/Hares_ear.png'),(92,'Hot Chocolate Chironomid Pupa Fly Pattern','','BC Fly Guys',7,11,'<p>This is one of our oldest and definitely one of our most productive chironomid fly patterns. A prefect cronie imitation for the pre gassed up pupaes on or near the bottom.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/QHtURoGdD20?si=kcBJqbPgv4liuBcu\" target=\"_blank\">Day Tripping Fly Patterns of the Day (S01E01) | Hot Chocolate Chironomid Pupa</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fishing this fly</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/XNMiv7zSp3M?si=WvcaboZPIz-n95OW\" target=\"_blank\">Stillwater Fly Fishing | Early Fall Chironomids - BCFLYGUYS Day Tripping S01E01</a></p>','This is one of our oldest and definitely one of our most productive chironomid fly patterns.','chironomid','flys/Chocolate.png'),(93,'Rusty Trombone','','',8,15,'<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/xt0-1rc6DVg?si=Lec5bCS5ed2gd7yH\" target=\"_blank\">Youtube</a></p>','How to tie An Easy Articulated Streamer I The Rusty Trombone','minnow','flys/rusty_trombone.png'),(94,'Screaming Viking Chironomid Pupa Fly Pattern','','BC Fly Guys',7,11,'<p><a href=\"https://youtube.com/shorts/LS9v9z12dBM?si=f4NN9cnFlyXYH2a8\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A really nice short about how to blend a colour.</p>','','chironomid','flys/screeming_viking.png'),(95,'Best Pellet Fly for Catching Stocked Trout | Easy Deer Hair Trout Pellet Fly','','',9,NULL,'<p>Here is one of the easiest deer hair applications for stocked trout in the form of a pellet imitation fly for your next stocker season. When fish are fed a series of pellets on the farm, these flies can imitate these pellets!</p>','Here is one of the easiest deer hair applications for stocked trout in the form of a pellet imitation fly','pellet','flys/pellet_fly.png'),(96,'Catatonic Leech','','',6,4,'<p>Dean Baayens wrote about the Catatonic Leech in the 1998 issue of Barry Mitchell&#39;s Alberta Fishing Guide. The secret to fishing this fly is to do nothing. Suspend it about 4 feet under an indicator and let it sit for twice as long as you can stand. Twitch it once, and let it sit. The trout will swim over and eat it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I tie it a little different than Dean does. Here is how I do it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://bamboorods.ca/Fly%27s/cleech-step1.jpg\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://bamboorods.ca/Fly%27s/cleech-step2.jpg\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://bamboorods.ca/Fly%27s/cleech-step2.jpg\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://bamboorods.ca/Fly%27s/cleech-step3.jpg\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Catatonic Leech</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hook: Mustad 75980 size 10-12<br />\r\nThread: olive<br />\r\nWeight: lead wire<br />\r\nTail: olive marabou, 2 bunches<br />\r\nBody: olive marabou, dubbed</p>','Dean Baayens wrote about the Catatonic Leech in the 1998 issue of Barry Mitchell\'s Alberta Fishing Guide.','leech','flys/Screenshot_from_2024-02-09_07-26-44.png'),(97,'CCF','','Barry Mitchell',5,11,'<p>The CFF was born of frustration.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Barry Mitchell and I stopped at Shirley and Bill Sara&rsquo;s, proprietors of the Bedside Manor on the Crowsnest River, to get permission to fish the loop south of the house. Bill and Shirley&rsquo;s daughter Dexine spotted us from the basement. Heading up the stairs and rounding the house, she called &quot;Can I come too&quot;? Dexine was 11 that summer and an accomplished fisherman. Barry tied on a Stimulator for her and she did well on Barry&rsquo;s side of the river but it wasn&rsquo;t long before she joined me on my side, the Stimulator gone.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Recalling another great Fly Fishing gal Iona Bengry, I tied Iona&rsquo;s favorite dry fly the Western Coachman to Dexine&rsquo;s leader. Dexine caught fish, lots of fish. Wasn&rsquo;t long before Barry and I were both casting the Western. But they don&rsquo;t last. Five fish or so and they are sinking, the herl broken or the hackle loose. My tie of the Western needed some upgrading.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Back at camp that night, supper over, dishes done, Scotch poured, I pondered what options I might use on the Western. For several years I had been using Macram&eacute; yarn as strike indicators so I decided to incorporate macram&eacute; as a wing plus some other tying tricks to make the Western last longer. The CFF was born that night. The name came later.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Material list:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Hook: Tiemco TMC 100 or equivalent in sizes 12&gt;16</li>\r\n	<li>Thread: Black Danville&rsquo;s 6/0 prewaxed</li>\r\n	<li>Tail: Brown Zylon or brown Macram&eacute; yarn</li>\r\n	<li>Body: 3 strands of peacock herl for size 12 hook</li>\r\n	<li>Wing: White Macram&eacute; yarn</li>\r\n	<li>Hackle: Grade # 3 or worse Hoffman or Metz Grizzly Cock Hackle</li>\r\n	<li>Glue: Thinned flex glues</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Tying notes:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Tail installation and trimming: use about &frac12; of a wooden match volume for the tail. Cut the tail off to about 3/8&quot; in length for a size 12 hook. Trim the tail to a arrow point.</li>\r\n	<li>Body construction: Peacock herl tied and wrapped by itself will fall apart after a few fish. Trim about 3/4&quot; of weaker herl from the tip end and tie it in at the hook bend. Make a loop of tying thread. Capture the herl and thread with your hackle pliers and twist into a rope. Wrap the herl up the hook. The herl MUST form a small bump at the tie off point [wing installation point] to force the wing upwards. I use a Griffin Rotary Hackle Pliers. It allows the herl/thread to be twisted readily.</li>\r\n	<li>Wing Construction: Use less than a wooden match volume for the wing tied in at the bump of herl. I use a 1 1/2&quot; length and trim away the excess later.</li>\r\n	<li>Hackle is tied in the normal dry fly position 3 turns only.</li>\r\n	<li>Wing Trimming: press the wing down so that it lays parallel with the body of the fly and trim the wing to the same length as the tail. The wing then should be pulled upward to 35-45 degrees for gluing.</li>\r\n	<li>Make several cuts from the tip of the wing towards the tie in point. This is to thin out the wing.</li>\r\n	<li>Glues: very thin flex type glues are needed for this fly. Place a drop on the top at the hackle/wing junction after the wing is trimmed. Separate and pull fibers of the macram&eacute; wing upwards and sideways keep the wing material fluffy. Don&rsquo;t let the glue bind the wing into a solid mass. The fly will not float.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Additional notes:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>As the wing floats the fly, good quality hackle is a waste and reduces hooking due to the stiff hackle forcing the fly out of the fish&rsquo;s mouth. Poorer quality hackle is webby and doesn&rsquo;t cause this problem. I use Hoffman or Metz Grade # 3 at 3 turns only.</li>\r\n	<li>Macram&eacute; yarns are now out of favor but are still available in limited colors from some craft shops. One hundred yard balls of yarn are available for less than $10.00. Other yarns might work as well, but macram&eacute; yarn&rsquo;s denier lends itself to the capture of air bubbles plus it has enough strength to support the fly</li>\r\n	<li>This fly is meant to float. The use of paste floatants will cause the fly&rsquo;s wing to adhere to itself making the wing unable to capture the air bubbles. If you must use floatant, use it sparingly and rub it so the wing still stands fluffy and upright.</li>\r\n	<li>I have tried a number of colors for the wing and body but have always returned to white wing, herl body and brown tail. The white wing allows us older folks to readily see the fly. Herl has some type of magic quality that catches fish and the brown tail seems to represent a trailing husk of some type.</li>\r\n	<li>I have tried both Grizzly and Coachman Brown hackle colors with success.</li>\r\n	<li>This fly is meant to be tied &quot;soft&quot;. There are no stiff wings, tails or hackle that will reduce the ability of the fly&rsquo;s hook to get into the fish&rsquo;s mouth.</li>\r\n	<li>For hook sizes 16-20 , I have left the hackle and tail off the fly. The fly still works.</li>\r\n	<li>If you want your CFF [or any fly for that matter] to last, find a hook remover that doesn&rsquo;t have serrated teeth and locking jaws. I use needle nose pliers with the teeth filed off of them.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>With a tail of Zylon, wing of macram&eacute;, loop twisted herl and some glue the basic fly was complete. On a trip later that summer, Mike Dell and I fished some cutthroat creeks. After fishing the same fly for 2 full days, I finally lost it in a cutthroat. That was after 115 trout. So the fly had a name C [Roman numeral for 100] F [fish] F [fly].</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But the surprises didn&rsquo;t end on its longevity. It worked great as a dry fly on a dry/dropper combination. There aren&rsquo;t many dry flies that you can pull underwater, release the tension and the fly pops to the surface. Although the CFF has been only used for a couple of years, it has accounted for a lot of fish by myself and others. It is now my &quot;go to&quot; fly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Enjoy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Don</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(This article originally appeared in Barry Mitchell&#39;s Alberta Fishing Guide 2001. Reproduced with permission.)</p>','The CFF was born of frustration.','ccf','flys/cff.jpg'),(98,'Blob','','',9,16,'<p>Advocates for traditional fly-fishing want to ban the blob fly pattern, considering it unsporting. Unlike traditional flies crafted to imitate natural forage, the blob, with its flashy appearance, was designed to trigger trout and is seen by many as an unfair advantage in competitive angling, making trout fishing too easy. Former England fly-fishing champion Chris Ogborne even left the national team in protest against the use of blobs, labeling them as cheating. He argues that the reliance on blobs undermines the core essence of fly-fishing, which traditionally involves imitating a trout&#39;s prey with hand-tied flies made from natural materials.</p>','Advocates for traditional fly-fishing want to ban the blob fly pattern, considering it unsporting.','blob','flys/blob.png'),(99,'BUNG WORMS OLIVE','','',6,NULL,'<p>A critically weighted worm pattern in the colour olive. Ideal for use under the drop back bung or pulled on a floating line and long leader, the extra quick sinking Tactical Drop Bead gives an exaggerated lift and drop movement which the fish find irresistible. If fishing these patterns under the bung, to maximise the number of takes to netted fish, use in conjunction with the Croston Drop Back Bung.</p>','Ideal for use under the drop back bung or pulled on a floating line and long leader, the extra quick sinking Tactical Drop Bead gives an exaggerated lift and drop movement which the fish find irresistible','worm','flys/BUNG_WORMS_OLIVE.jpg'),(100,'Buzzer with a tail','','',6,11,'<p>A nice all round searching fly.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is an accompaning video with it.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/r6sAj2yxtS4?si=24cwxgRpYtWI1SUn&amp;t=190\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a></p>','A nice all round searching fly.','buzzer-with-a-tail','flys/buzzer_with_a_tail.png'),(101,'Cruncher','','',6,NULL,'<h2>About the Cruncher Trout Fly</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The Cruncher is an excellent still water all rounder.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt is an all-encompassing pattern that represents a variety of important food sources for trout such as larva, buzzers and emergers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis fly is usually most productive when fished on an intermediate or floating line with a gentle figure of eight retrieve.</p>','The Cruncher is an excellent still water all rounder.','cruncher','flys/Cruncher_aaAx7Si.png');
